# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen graduated from Thomas Jefferson High School in San Antonio, Texas.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He received a Bachelor of Science degree from Texas A&M University in 1952, a Master of Science degree from Stevens Institute of Technology in 1958, and an honorary doctorate from Stevens in 1982.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen joined NASA in 1962 and served in key leadership roles critical to the success of the flights and lunar landings of the Apollo Program.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] From 1969 to 1972, Cohen was the manager for the Apollo Command and Service Modules.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He oversaw the design, development, production and test flights of the Space Shuttles as manager of NASA's Space Shuttle Orbiter Project Office from 1972 to 1982.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After serving as Director of Engineering at Johnson for several years, he was named director of the center in 1986, serving in that post until 1993.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After his retirement from NASA, Cohen taught mechanical engineering design at Texas A&M University.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] In 2000, he was appointed Professor Emeritus, and in 2010, he was awarded an honorary Doctor of Letters.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] The **administrator of the National Aeronautics and Space Administration** is the highest-ranking official of NASA, the national space agency of the United States.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] The administrator is NASA's chief decision maker, responsible for providing clarity to the agency's vision and serving as a source of internal leadership within NASA.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] The office holder also has an important place within United States space policy, and is assisted by a deputy administrator.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] The administrator is appointed by the president of the United States, with the advice and consent of the United States Senate, and thereafter serves at the president's pleasure.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] Jared Isaacman has served as the administrator since December 18, 2025.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] The administrator serves as NASA's chief executive officer, accountable to the president for the leadership necessary to achieve the agency's mission.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] This leadership requires articulating the agency's vision, setting its programmatic and budget priorities and internal policies, and assessing agency performance.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] Keith Glennan; during his term he brought together the disparate projects in space development research in the US.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] Within a short time after NASA's formal organization, Glennan incorporated several organizations involved in space exploration projects from other federal agencies into NASA.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] He brought in part of the Naval Research Laboratory and created the Goddard Space Flight Center.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] He also incorporated several disparate satellite programs, two lunar probes, and the research effort to develop a million pound force (4.4 MN) thrust, single-chamber rocket engine from the U.S.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] Department of Defense's (DOD) Advanced Research Projects Agency.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] In December 1958 Glennan also acquired control of the Jet Propulsion Laboratory, a contractor facility operated by the California Institute of Technology.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] In 1960, Glennan obtained the transfer to NASA of the Army Ballistic Missile Agency, located at Huntsville, Alabama, and renamed it the Marshall Space Flight Center.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] Webb, served from 1961 to 1968, from the beginning of the Kennedy administration through the end of the Johnson administration, thus overseeing each of the critical first crewed missions throughout the Mercury and Gemini programs until days before the launch of the first Apollo mission.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] During Webb's administration, NASA developed from a loose collection of research centers to a coordinated organization.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] He had a key role in creating the Manned Spacecraft Center, later the Johnson Space Center, in Houston.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] Despite the pressures to focus on the Apollo program, Webb ensured that NASA carried out a program of planetary exploration with the Mariner and Pioneer space programs.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] Webb was an early champion of space telescopes, like the one that would later bear his name.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] Encouraged by Kennedy and Johnson, Webb made racial integration a priority for the agency.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] NASA publicly supported the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and initiated a series of innovative programs aimed at increasing black participation including specifically targeting black colleges and schools with recruitment programs.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] The only person to hold the post twice is James C.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] During his first administration at NASA, Fletcher was responsible for beginning the Space Shuttle effort, as well as the Viking program that sent landers to Mars.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] He oversaw the Skylab missions and approved the Voyager space probes and the Apollo–Soyuz Test Project.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] He returned to NASA following the *Challenger* disaster.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] Daniel Goldin held the post for the longest term (nearly 10 years), and is best known for pioneering the "faster, better, cheaper" approach to space programs.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] The current administrator is entrepreneur and philanthropist Jared Isaacman, who was nominated by President Donald Trump on November 5, 2025.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] He replaced Sean Duffy, who served as acting administrator from July 9, 2025 to December 17, 2025.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/administrator-of-nasa] Jared Isaacman was nominated by Trump (while he was president-elect) on December 4, 2024, but his nomination was withdrawn on May 31, reportedly because of his connections to Elon Musk and donations towards Democratic, anti-Trump politicians.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-howard-engineer] Howard was born in Washington, D.C., in 1905.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-howard-engineer] He obtained his BSc in electrical engineering from Purdue University in 1927.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-howard-engineer] After his graduation in 1927, Howard started his lifelong career at the General Electric Company in Schenectady, New York as electrical engineer.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-howard-engineer] He advanced rapidly various positions, and moved into steam turbine activities in 1941.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-howard-engineer] In World War II at General Electric, Howard managed the development of aircraft gas turbine engine for the United States Air Force, and developed the TG 100 and TG 180 turboprop engine.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-howard-engineer] Coffin Award by General Electric for his "accomplishments in connection with the design and development of the TG100 and TG180 aircraft gas turbines." In 1954, he was awarded the honorary degree of doctor of engineering by Purdue University.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-howard-engineer] In 1962, he had been elected Fellow of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, and in 1964, he was awarded the ASME Medal.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-m-lovelace] He graduated with a Bachelor of Science in chemistry from the University of Florida in Gainesville in 1951, received a Master of Science in organic chemistry in 1952 and became a Doctor of Philosophy in 1954, also in organic chemistry.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-m-lovelace] Lovelace served in the United States Air Force from 1954 to 1956.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-m-lovelace] Thereafter, he began work as a government scientist at the Air Force Materials Laboratory (AFML), Wright-Patterson Air Force Base, Dayton, Ohio.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-m-lovelace] There he initially did work in the field of fluorine and polymer chemistry.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-m-lovelace] These efforts on fluorocarbon and inorganic polymers extended the useful temperature range over which polymers could be used.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-m-lovelace] In January 1964, he was named as chief scientist of the Air Force Materials Laboratory.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-m-lovelace] In this role, he worked to realize the potential of very high strength, very light weight fibers being consolidated in a new class of composites.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-m-lovelace] In 1967, he was named director of the Air Force Materials Laboratory, and in October 1972, he was named director of science and technology for the Air Force Systems Command at its Headquarters, Andrews Air Force Base, Maryland.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-m-lovelace] In this role, he provided technical guidance and management policy to eleven Air Force Systems Command Laboratories, five Liaison Officers, and the Command's European Office of Aerospace Research.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-m-lovelace] In September 1973, he became the principal deputy to the assistant secretary of the Air Force for research and development.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-m-lovelace] In this role, he advised and assisted the assistant secretary in his direction of the entire Air Force Research and Development Program.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-m-lovelace] In September 1974, he left the Department of Defense to become the associate administrator of the NASA Office of Aeronautics and Space Technology.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-m-lovelace] As the associate administrator for aeronautics and space technology, he was responsible for the management of the research program that will provide the basic science and technology advances that will be required for future military and civil aircraft, and the systems to exploit and explore space.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-m-lovelace] During his career he became a Fellow in the American Astronautical Society; he also became a member of the National Academy of Engineering, American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics, the Air Force Association, Sigma Xi, and Phi Beta Kappa.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-m-lovelace] In June 1981, Lovelace was also presented with the Presidential Citizens Medal by President Ronald Reagan.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-m-lovelace] He retired from NASA to accept a position as Corporate Vice President – Science and Engineering with the General Dynamics Corporation at St.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-m-lovelace] By 1985 he had become Corporate Vice President and General Manager of General Dynamics' Space System Division.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-m-lovelace] Later he became chief architect and head of the corporation's commercial Atlas space launch initiative, overseeing development of the Atlas I, II, IIA and IIAS launch vehicles.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-m-lovelace] In 1991 he was named senior vice president for Space Policy and Technology at General Dynamics, operating from an office in Washington, D.C., as well as serving as chairman of the company's Commercial Launch Services subsidiary.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/alan-m-lovelace] Lovelace died at an assisted living facility in Melbourne, Florida, on April 18, 2018.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Albert Kingsbury was born in Morris, Illinois and graduated from Cuyahoga Falls High School, OH in 1880.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] In addition to his interest in tribology and bearings, Kingsbury enjoyed the world of arts, history, and letters.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] He devoted much time to the study of foreign languages.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury died in Greenwich, Connecticut 1943, and is buried at the Green-Wood Cemetery, Brooklyn, New York.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] In 1884, Kingsbury attended the University of Akron to study Scientific-Latin courses.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] He dropped out and worked as a machine apprentice in Cuyahoga Falls.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury credited this as an important experience that led him to advance his career in engineering.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury resumed his formal education at Ohio State University, but he again dropped out to work as a machinist with the Warner and Swasey Company in Cleveland.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury received his mechanical engineering degree from Cornell University in 1887.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] It was at Cornell that he met Professor Robert Henry Thurston.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Professor Thurston was instrumental in shaping Kingsbury's interest in bearings and tribology.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Working under Professor Thurston, Kingsbury conducted tests on bearing materials for the Pennsylvania Railroad.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] His craftsmanship, honed by his experience in machine shops, allowed Kingsbury to fit half-bushings to the journal by scraping.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] His hand fitting produced the small tolerances that promoted film lubrication.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] These bearings, when ran showed no measurable signs of wear, and was Kingsbury's prompt to the creation of the thrust bearings which now bear his name.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury pursued a teaching position at the University of New Hampshire.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Within two years, he was a professor of Mechanical Engineering courses at the university.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] His new position at the university allowed him to continue pursuing his interest in lubrication.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] During his time at the University of New Hampshire, he created an innovative test machine to measure friction in coarse pitch, lubricated screw threads at loads of up to 14,000 psi.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] The usefulness of this invention received mixed reviews from the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME).
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] His research also covered fluid lubricated bearings, and he published a paper entitled "Experiments with an Air Lubricated Bearing".
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] It was at this university that he envisioned the Kingsbury thrust bearing.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury joined the Worcester Polytechnic Institute to continue pursuing his interest in lubrication.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] He secured expansions for laboratory facilities and funding to continue his tests on a centrally pivoted thrust bearing with the aid of his students.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury's research at the University of New Hampshire led him to conceive an early Kingsbury bearing that consisted of several stationary arc segments facing a thrust collar on the rotating shaft.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Each segment would have a boss on the side away from the thrust collar, allowing it to tilt and form an oil wedge that would carry the thrust.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury tested this new bearing with a modified version of his earlier screw thread testing machine.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] The bearing was successful with pressures of up to 4,000 psi at speeds of 285 rpm.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] This pressure exceeded that for common collar-type bearings by a factor of 80 to 100, thus proving the promise of the Kingsbury bearing.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury joined the Westinghouse Electric Company in Pittsburgh as a general engineer.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] He used this as an opportunity to advance the development of his thrust bearings in an industrial setting.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Unfortunately, the first test of his thrust bearing was a failure.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] His bearing overheated during the test and was discarded.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] This made the company skeptical of Kingsbury's invention, but Westinghouse's skepticism did not dent Kingsbury's enthusiasm.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury would later fund his own test that proved his bearings successful.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Unfortunately, Westinghouse decided to stick to more conventional ball bearings for their motors.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury tried to file for a U.S. patent during 1907.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] His initial application was rejected as a British patent had been granted in 1905 to A.G.M.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury was able to demonstrate that his 1898 test at the University of New Hampshire predated Michell's work, so in 1910 Kingsbury was awarded US patent No.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] 947242 for the tilting pad thrust bearing.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury would eventually run his own business with the Westinghouse Machine Co. building his bearings.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] This allowed him to actively pursue applications for his newly patented thrust bearing.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] His first chance came when the Pennsylvania Water and Power Co. gave him the opportunity to demonstrate his bearing on their power generator at the Susquehanna River.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] His first bearing was a failure as it was immediately destroyed by Hillson wiping.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Fortunately for Kingsbury, the Pennsylvania Water and Power Co. gave him a second chance.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] His bearing succeeded this time, and worked flawlessly for the next 25 years.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] When it was inspected after 25 years, there was so little evidence of wear that it was calculated that the bearing would last 1,300 to 1,700 years.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] The same bearing is still operating smoothly today.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] In 1921, the Kingsbury thrust bearing had become so popular that Westinghouse could no longer keep up with the demand, thus prompting Kingsbury to set up his own manufacturing plant.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury continued to pursue his interest in bearings and tribology later in his life.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] One of his greatest achievements was his analysis of the effects of side leakage of lubricants from bearings.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] By recognizing the analogy in the equations for lubrication and those for electrical flow in a conductive fluid and variable depth, Kingsbury was able to make complicated predictions of slider load capacity well before the advent of computers.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury made important contributions to the area of boundary lubrication.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] He was the first to recognize that some fluid lubricants possess a friction-reducing property that is independent of viscosity, which he called 'oiliness'.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] His findings were of great significance since they demonstrated that the hydrodynamic theory of lubrication did not describe completely the lubricating mechanism of fluids.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Later work by Hardy and Doubleday showed that this property was related to the ability of polar lubricants to adsorb and form close-packed monolayers on the sliding surfaces.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] for his wide-ranging contributions to the field, Kingsbury was named as one of the 23 "Men of Tribology" by Duncan Dowson.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury received many accolades for his contributions to science and engineering.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] He was awarded the Gold Medal of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers in 1931; the Elliott Cresson Medal of the Franklin Institute; and honorary doctorates from the University of New Hampshire and Worcester Polytechnic Institute.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] He was elected Honorary Member of ASME in 1940.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] The Kingsbury Hall at the University of New Hampshire also pays homage to the great inventor.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/albert-kingsbury] Albert Kingsbury was inducted into the National Inventors Hall of Fame.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] Swasey was born near Exeter, New Hampshire to Nathaniel and Abigail Swasey.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] He apprenticed as a machinist at the Exeter Machine Works and was afterwards employed at Pratt & Whitney.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] As his career progressed, he became a foreman in the gear-cutting section.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] He developed a new technique for making gear-tooth cutters.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] In 1880, he and Warner formed their eponymous firm, which quickly moved to Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] Swasey would perform the engineering and machine development at this company.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] The close friends Warner and Swasey built their homes next to each other on Euclid Avenue in Cleveland, a street that was known as "Millionaire's Row".
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] In addition to army ordnance contracts, the firm of Warner & Swasey became notable for their work on astronomical observatories and equipment.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] The founders were interested in astronomy as an avocation, and in the field's quest for better optical telescopes, which was burgeoning at the time.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] They also realized that obtaining contracts to build large astronomical observatories would provide publicity for their company.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] In 1885, Swasey completed work at McCormick Observatory on the 45-foot dome, which was the largest in the world, and had a unique, 3 shutter design.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] In 1887, Swasey built the mount for the 36-inch refracting telescope at Lick Observatory.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] In 1898, he manufactured a dividing engine for the U.S.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] Naval Observatory that was used to make the meridian circles.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] Both the building and dome of the Dominion Astrophysical Observatory were made by Warner and Swasey Co.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] Other observatory telescopes and components were built by the company at the Kenwood Observatory, Yerkes Observatory, Argentine National Observatory, the Swasey Observatory at Denison University, and the Case School of Applied Science Observatory.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] From 1904 until 1905, he was the president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] Both Warner and Swasey were amateur astronomers.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] When they became trustees of the Case School of Applied Science, they donated to the school their private observatory, which they had built between their neighboring houses in East Cleveland.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] Relocated to a new building, this became the Warner and Swasey Observatory.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] The observatory maintained by the department today is still known by this name today.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] Swasey Hall (1917, "懷士堂"), a red brick hall, is the landmark of Sun Yat-sen University, one of the top colleges in China.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] It was named after Swasey for his USD$25000 donation to the then university Christian YMCA society hall.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] The chimes in the chapel were included as a memorial to his wife, Lavinia Marston Swasey.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/ambrose-swasey] The Warner & Swasey Company he cofounded would continue until 1980, when it was acquired by Bendix Corporation.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/asme-medal] The **ASME Medal**, created in 1920, is the highest award bestowed by the ASME (founded as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers) Board of Governors for "eminently distinguished engineering achievement".
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/asme-medal] The award has been presented every year since 1996 (first medalist was awarded in 1921), and it consists of a $15,000 honorarium, a certificate, a travel supplement not to exceed $750, and a gold medal inscribed with the words, "What is not yet, may be".
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/asme-medal] ASME also gives out a number of other awards yearly, including the Edwin F.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/asme-medal] Church Medal, the Holley medal, and the Soichiro Honda medal.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] A **Bachelor of Science** (**BS**, **BSc**, **SB**, or **ScB**; from the Latin **scientiae baccalaureus**) is a bachelor's degree awarded upon the completion and fulfillment of the requirements of an undergraduate program.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] The first university to admit a student to the degree of Bachelor of Science was the University of London in 1860.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] In the United States, the Lawrence Scientific School first conferred the degree in 1851, followed by the University of Michigan in 1855.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Whether Bachelor of Science or Bachelor of Arts degrees are awarded in particular subjects varies between universities.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] For example, an economics student may graduate as a Bachelor of Arts in one university but as a Bachelor of Science in another, and occasionally, both options are offered.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Some universities follow the Oxford and Cambridge tradition that even graduates in mathematics and the sciences become Bachelors of Arts, while other institutions offer only the Bachelor of Science degree, even in non-science fields.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] In some institutions, there are historical and traditional reasons that govern the granting of BS or BA degrees regardless of the disciplines offered.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Georgetown University's School of Foreign Service awards the Bachelor of Science in Foreign Service (BSFS) degrees to all of its undergraduates, although many students major in humanities-oriented fields such as international history or culture and politics.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School awards the BS in Economics to all of its undergraduates, regardless if the candidates major in economics or not.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] The London School of Economics offers BSc degrees in practically all subject areas, even those normally associated with the arts and humanities.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Northwestern University's School of Communication grants the Bachelor of Science in Journalism degrees in all of its programs of study, including theater, dance, and radio/television/film.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Meanwhile, the Oxbridge universities almost exclusively award the BA as a first degree.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] The decision to grant a BS or BA degree at some institutions also depends on the constituent colleges, even when the candidate pursues the same or similar subjects.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] For instance, Cornell University offers a BS degree in computer science from its College of Engineering and a BA degree in computer science from its College of Arts and Sciences.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Likewise, for candidates majoring in computer science, Columbia University offers BS degrees for those enrolled in the School of Engineering and Applied Science but awards BA degrees for graduates of Columbia College.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] At Harvard University, the same undergraduate degree in computer science can be an A.B. if taken at Harvard College or Harvard John A.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Paulson School of Engineering and Applied Sciences, and an A.L.B. at Harvard Extension School.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] In Argentina most university degrees are given as a license in a discipline.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] They are specific to a field and awarded to students upon completion of a course of study which lasts at least four and usually five years.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] In most cases, at the end of a course and as a mandatory condition for its completion (and ultimately, to obtain a degree), students are compelled to produce an original research project related to their field.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] This project is usually referred to as a thesis (although the term actually corresponds to post-graduate studies).
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] In Australia, the BSc is generally a three to four-year degree.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] An honours year or a master's by research degree is required to progress on to the stage of Doctor of Philosophy (PhD).
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] In New Zealand, in some cases, the honours degree comprises an additional postgraduate qualification.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] In other cases, students with strong performance in their second or third year, are invited to extend their degree to an additional year, with a focus on research, granting access to doctoral programs.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] In South Africa, the BSc is taken over three years, while the postgraduate BSc (Hons) entails an additional year of study.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Admission to the honours degree is on the basis of a sufficiently high average in the BSc major; an honours degree is required for MSc level study, and admission to a doctorate is via the MSc.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] In Brazil, a Bachelor of Science degree is an undergraduate academic degree and is equivalent to a BSc (Hons).
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Some disciplines are prerequisite to others and in some universities, the student is not allowed to course any discipline for the entire next period if he was unsuccessful in just one prerequisite discipline of the present period.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Usually, the Bachelor of Science courses demand a one-year mandatory probation period by the end of the course (internship in the specific professional area, like a training period), followed by relatively elaborate written and oral evaluations.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] To be a professor, a Bachelor of Sciences is required to get a Licenciature degree, which lasts on top of the periods already studied until getting the BSc (Hons), plus 2 to 3 periods (1 to 1.5 years).
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] With a master's degree (MSc) is also possible, which takes 3 to 5 periods more (1.5 to 2.5 years more).
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] In Chile, the completion of a university program leads to an academic degree as well as a professional title.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] The academic degree equivalent to Bachelor of Science is "*Licenciado en Ciencias*", which can be obtained as a result of completing a 4–6 year program.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] However, in most cases, 4-year programs will grant a Bachelor of Applied Science (Spanish: *"Licenciatura en Ciencias Aplicadas"*) degree, while other 4-year programs will not grant to an academic degree.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Many universities in Europe are changing their systems into the BA/MA system and in doing so also offering the full equivalent of a BSc or MSc (see Bologna Process).
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Universities in the Czech Republic are changing their systems into the Bachelor of Science/Master of Science system and in doing so also offering the full equivalent of a BSc (Bc.) or MSc (Mgr./Ing.).
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] In Germany, there are two kinds of universities: *Universitäten* and *Fachhochschulen* (which are also called University of Applied Sciences).
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] *Universitäten* and *Fachhochschulen* – both also called *Hochschulen* - are legally equal, but *Fachhochschulen* have the reputation of being more related to practice and have no legal right to offer PhD programmes.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] The BSc in Germany is equivalent to the BSc(Hons) in the United Kingdom.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Many universities in German-speaking countries are changing their systems to the BA/MA system and in doing so also offering the full equivalent of a BSc.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] In Germany the BA normally lasts between three and four years (six to eight semesters) and between 180 and 240 ECTS must be earned.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Bachelor of Science (BSc) is usually a three-year graduate program in India offered by state and central universities.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Some independent private colleges can also offer BS degrees with minimum changes in curriculum.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] BSc is different from Bachelor of Engineering (BE) or Bachelor of Technology (BTech).
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Three exceptions are the BSc (Research) course offered by the Indian Institute of Science which lasts four years with an option to stay back an extra year for a master's thesis, the B.Sc.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Among the top choices for students, BSc colleges in Delhi are known for their academic excellence, modern infrastructure, and wide range of specializations offered under the NEP 2020 framework.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] From session 2022–23, the University of Delhi implemented NEP 2020 under which a bachelor's degree became a 4-year degree with multiple exit and entry options.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] A student receives a BSc (research) field of study or BSc (honours) field of multidisciplinary studies after the 4th year.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Commonly in Ireland, graduands are admitted to the degree of Bachelor of Science after having completed a programme in one or more of the sciences.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] These programmes may take different lengths of time to complete.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] In Ireland, the former BS was changed to BSc (Hons), which is awarded after four years.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] The BSc (Ord) is awarded after three years.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Formerly at the University of Oxford, the degree of BSc was a postgraduate degree; this former degree, still actively granted, has since been renamed MSc.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Commonly in British Commonwealth countries, graduands are admitted to the degree of Bachelor of Science after having completed a programme in one or more of the sciences.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] A Bachelor of Science receives the designation BSc for an ordinary degree and BSc (Hons) for an honours degree.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] In England, Wales and Northern Ireland an honours degree is typically completed over a three-year period, though there are a few intensified two-year courses (with less vacation time).
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Bachelor's degrees (without honours) were typically completed in two years for most of the twentieth century.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] In Scotland, where access to university is possible after one less year of secondary education, degree courses have a foundation year making the total course length four years.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] In Canada, Mexico, and the United States, it is most often a four-year undergraduate degree, typically in engineering, computer science, mathematics, economics, finance, business, or the natural sciences.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] There are, however, some colleges and universities, notably in the province of Quebec, that offer three-year degree programs.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Bangladesh (four or five years), Pakistan (four or five years), Indonesia (four or five years), Nigeria (four or five years), six months dedicated to SIWES (Students Industrial Work Exchange Scheme) but for most sciences and all engineering courses only.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] A semester for project work/thesis not excluding course work during the bachelor thesis.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Excluding one year for the compulsory National Youth Service Corps (NYSC), para-military and civil service.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] North Macedonia, Sierra Leone (four years dedicated to coursework), Slovenia (four or five years), Sudan (five years for BSc honours degree and four years for BSc ordinary degree), and Syria.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] In Algeria, the student presents a thesis in front of a Jury at the end of the fifth year.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] Some universities in Canada (such as University of British Columbia and Vancouver Island University) have most of their science and applied science students extend their degree by a year compared to other institutions.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] In Chile, some undergraduate majors such as engineering and geology are designed as six-year programs.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] However, in practice it is not uncommon for students to complete such programs over the course of ten years, while studying full-time without leaves of absence.
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] This is in part due to a strict grading system where the highest grade of a typical class can be as low as 60% (C-).
[src:aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator/bachelor-of-science] There are studies that suggest a direct correlation between reduced social mobility and differences unique to the Chilean higher education system.
